ic, anti-modern, and narrow.Drawing on monographs, edited collections, journal articles, and society publications, Willa Cather: The Critical Conversation provides Cather scholars and students at the graduate and undergraduate levels with an accessible overview of Cather's critical reception through the first two decades of the twenty-first century. In addition to providing a valuable resource for research and teaching on Cather, the book also speaks to broader issues such ascanon formation and historical trends in literary criticism that are relevant to American literature and culture as a whole. This book provides a solid understanding of the major issues in Cather criticism over time, with an eye toward how the conversation may continue for decades to come. Kelsey Squire is Associate Professor of English at Ohio Dominican University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNovelists, AmericanvBiographyy20th century. 0aWomen and literaturexHistoryy20th centuryzUnited States. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican culture.  aAmerican fiction.  aAmerican literature.  aCather scholarship.  aWilla Cather.  acanon formation.  acritical reception.  acultural values.  aliterary analysis.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary trends.  atwentieth-century authors.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446861?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446861/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles